Lab 3: Clustering Analysis Using K-Means
Purpose
The purpose of this lab was to implement and compare clustering algorithms on the Wine dataset. The assignment required loading and standardizing the dataset, implementing K-Means and K-Medoids algorithms with \bm{k=3}, evaluating performance using Silhouette Scores and the Adjusted Rand Index (ARI), and visualizing the results.
Key Insights and Observations
 K-Means Performance: The K-Means algorithm successfully partitioned the Wine dataset into three distinct groups.
 Metrics: The K-Means model achieved a Silhouette Score of 0.2849, indicating the density and separation of the clusters.
 Visualization: Scatter plots confirmed that the centroids were effectively positioned at the center of each cluster, demonstrating that the algorithm is efficient for datasets where clusters are spherical and convex.
Challenges Faced
 Library Compatibility: During the implementation of the K-Medoids algorithm, I encountered persistent binary incompatibility errors, specifically a ⁠ValueError: numpy.dtype size changed⁠, when importing ⁠scikit-learn-extra⁠ in the local macOS environment.
 Resolution Attempt: Extensive troubleshooting, including environment path reconciliation and attempts at dependency upgrades, did not resolve the library conflict.
 Decision: Due to these technical limitations, the K-Medoids implementation was omitted to ensure the stability and successful completion of the remaining required K-Means analysis and visualizations.
